                  <h2>How to manage exam stress</h2>
                </div>
                <p>Think of how you would feel if your child compares you with the parents of his friends who are maybe
                  smarter, richer, or have better houses and jobs? It won’t feel good. Likewise for children. It makes
                  them feel worthless and unwanted.</p>
                <p>Your child wants to hear that you believe he can do well in exam, and only you can encourage him.
                  Take an interest in his interests and together explore new career options for him. Give him your
                  support in whatever career route he chooses as long as he approaches with passion and determination.
                </p>
                <ul class="my_list">
                  <li>Learn to recognize when you're stressing out. A break or a chat with someone who knows the
                    pressure you're under will get things into perspective.</li>
                  <li>Avoid comparing your abilities with your friends or batch mates. Those "Oh my God I've only read
                    poem 17 times" conversations are such a wind up. Everyone approaches revision in different ways, so
                    just make sure you've chosen the method that works best for you. Make a realistic timetable. Stick
                    to it.</li>
                  <li>Eat right. Treat yourself like a well honed machine - eat fresh fruit and veg and have a proper
                    breakfasts. Fuel your brain as well as your body - no one can think straight on coffee and
                    chocolate.</li>
                  <li>Sleep well. Wind down before bed and don't revise it on your bed. Get your eight hours.</li>
                  <li>Exercise. Nothing de-stresses the mind faster than physical activity, so build it into your
                    timetable.Doing meditation and ../images/blogs/blog3/ is good for the health and it will also keep
                    your mind calm and relaxed.</li>
                  <li>Quit the bad habits. Cigarettes and alcohol never stopped anyone being stressed for very long.
                  </li>
                  <li>Panic is often triggered by hyperventilating (quick, shallow breaths). So if you feel yourself
                    losing it during the exam, sit back for a moment and control your breathing. Deep breath in and out
                    through the nose, counting to five each way.</li>
                  <li>It doesn't matter what your batchmate wrote for Question 3(b), it's too late to go back and change
                    your answers, so it will just make you worry even more. So don't take stress about what you have
                    performed in the examination, take a deep breath and everything will be fine. </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
